complete_model_interaction.output:
Step 1 – Psychological Mechanisms:
• Participants track the benefits of each option by integrating the outcomes shown during the forced‐choice trials. This gives rise to an exploitation signal based on the observed (sampled) mean rewards.
• They also “explore” when there is less information about an option. Because the forced-choice design sometimes exposes one option only once (unequal information) and the other three times, there is an asymmetric uncertainty (information) signal.
• The net decision is assumed to arise from a combination of the exploitation (expected reward) and an exploration bonus that is weighted by the available horizon (free‐choice count).
• Since in the design the forced‐choice sampling difference is independent of the underlying reward difference, the model should include an additive bonus term that factors in the predetermined information imbalance.
• Mathematically, we can capture the process by taking a linear combination of the difference in the observed expected rewards and the (pre‐computed) information bonus. The bonus term is modulated by the horizon (with a factor of 0 when only one free choice is available and reaching full effect when six free choices are available).
• The model has two learnable parameters: one scaling the exploitation value (alpha) and one scaling the exploration bonus (delta). Their bounds are set to generous finite values to aid parameter recovery.

Step 2 – Mathematical Form:
For each free‐choice trial (forced_choice = FALSE) we compute the utility difference between choosing option 1 and option 0 as

  U = alpha * (expected_reward1 – expected_reward0) + delta * ((horizon – 1)/5) * info_bonus

Here, info_bonus is a calculated variable that equals:
  +2 if option 1 was sampled less than option 0 (i.e. in the unequal forced‐choice condition),
  –2 if option 0 was sampled less than option 1,
  0 if the forced sampling was equal.

This utility value is then fed into a logistic function (outside our model) to yield choice probabilities. Negative values of U make option 1 less likely, and positive values make it more likely.

Below is the formal model specification.

<MODEL>
U = alpha*(expected_reward1 - expected_reward0) + delta*((horizon - 1)/5)*info_bonus
</MODEL>

